## VERIFICATION STEP — BEFORE PRODUCING OUTPUT

For every clause in the expected list for the detected contract type,
search the contract text for any paragraph that explicitly describes
or defines that clause concept.

Do not rely on memory or assumption. Read the actual contract text.

If you cannot find any paragraph that explicitly covers a clause concept
— mark it as ABSENT.

If a clause concept appears under a different heading or wording
— it still counts as PRESENT.

Only after completing this verification for every expected clause
— produce the final output.

## STEP 3 — SCAN THE CONTRACT

Carefully read the entire contract and determine if each expected clause appears.

Important rules:

• A clause counts as PRESENT even if wording differs from standard templates.
• A clause counts as PRESENT even if spread across multiple paragraphs.
• Headings alone DO NOT count as clause presence.
A clause should be considered PRESENT only if the contract explicitly
describes or defines the clause concept.
References to a concept alone do NOT count as clause presence.
Before reporting a clause as missing, scan the document twice to ensure the concept does not appear under different wording or headings.
Only report clauses that are completely missing from the contract.

---

========================================================
QUALITY RULES
========================================================

1. BE EXHAUSTIVE: Check every standard clause for the contract type. A typical employment agreement has 10-15 standard clauses; an MSA has 15-20. If your output has fewer than 3-4 findings for a standard contract, you have likely missed items — re-scan the document.
2. DO NOT flag clauses that are adequately covered, even if worded differently from a template. Substance over form.
3. DO NOT hallucinate clauses that are not standard for the detected contract type.
4. Order results by importance: all "high" items first, then "medium", then "low".
5. total_missing must exactly equal the length of the missing_clauses list.
6. The summary must be a brief (2-4 sentences) overall assessment covering:
   - The detected contract type.
   - Total count with severity breakdown (e.g., "3 high, 2 medium, 1 low").
   - The most critical gap(s) and their potential real-world impact on the parties.

